     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "'Depending on how you capitalize it, \"Rag\" usually refers to one of two things:\\n\\n### 1. RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)\\nIn the context of Artificial Intelligence, **RAG** stands for **Retrieval-Augmented Generation**. It is a technique used to make Large Language Models (LLMs) like GPT-4 more accurate and up-to-date.\\n\\nHere is how it works:\\n*   **Retrieval:** When you ask a question, the system first searches through an external, trusted database (like your company\\'s internal documents or a specific set of PDFs) to find information relevant to your question.\\n*   **Augmentation:** It takes that retrieved information and attaches it to your original question.\\n*   **Generation:** It sends both your question and the retrieved information to the AI model to generate an answer.\\n\\n**Why is it useful?**\\nStandard AI models rely only on what they learned during training, which can become outdated or lead to \"hallucinations\" (making things up). RAG allows the AI to look up facts before answering, ensuring the response is based on specific, real-time data.\\n\\n### 2. Rag (The Fabric)\\nA **rag** is a piece of old cloth, typically one that is torn, worn out, or used for cleaning. It is commonly used for dusting, washing cars, or cleaning up spills.\\n\\n***\\n\\n**Which one were you looking for?**\\nIf you were asking about AI technology, the answer is **Retrieval-Augmented Generation**. If you were asking about a household item, it is a piece of scrap fabric.'"
      ]
     },
